Ce que je dis à mes amis non-américains
CAMBRIDGE – I travel often abroad and my foreign friends always ask, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what is happening in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
Firstly, be careful not to misinterpret the 2016 elections.
Contrary to some comments, the American political system has not been swept by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against elites.
Donald Trump tapped into a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Yet Trump came within nearly three million votes of winning the popular vote.
He won the election by mobilizing populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If just tens of thousands of votes had gone differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
This said, Trump's victory raises the real issue of the rise in social and regional inequalities in the United States.
The latest bestseller by J.D. Vance, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the big difference between California and the Appalachians.
Research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among white Americans with low incomes and no college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically occupied the lower end of inequalities.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without higher education were around 30% below those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Moreover, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for white working-class Americans, has significantly declined over the last generation, to only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to make things happen and bring jobs back to the manufacturing industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may well make their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you shouldn't underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous disregard for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is monopolizing the audience's attention, and that the best way to do this is to make extreme statements without worrying about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and in academic circles does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his permanent self-centered campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that deters some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center in order to attract more support.
C'est ce que George W. Bush a fait avec succès en 2001.
Trump, en revanche, proclame qu'il a remporté le vote populaire et en agissant comme si cela était vraiment le cas, plaît à ses électeurs de base.
Bien que Trump ait fait de solides nominations centristes au Département de la Défense, d'État et la Sécurité nationale, son choix pour l'Agence de Protection de l'Environnement et pour le ministère de la Santé et des Services aux personnes se situent aux extrêmes du Parti républicain.
Son personnel à la Maison Blanche est divisé entre des idéologues et des pragmatiques - et il entend satisfaire les deux camps à la fois.
Quatrièmement, il ne faut pas sous-estimer les institutions américaines.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is a dangerous narcissist like Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
Although the United States has many problems, it is not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as polarized.
In the design of the United States Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure that the government would be harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that makes the exercise of these powers difficult.
A joke about this topic says that the founders created a political system so that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or for anyone else.
Inefficiency has been put to the service of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its early stages, and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have protected this balance of powers within the administration, as Madison intended.
And the permanent executive service officials still carry significant influence.
Finally, my friends are wondering what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Frankly, I don't know, but I am less worried about the rise of China than about the rise of Trump.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite the problems with the international order under American leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can be certain that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first candidate from a major party in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, statements by Trump and his members suggest that he may continue to do so.
The power to constrain and persuade the United States, after all, largely comes from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The Trump Budget Director speaks of a budget of coercive power, with budget cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other members of the government argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with bilateral « fair and balanced » arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to be able to reassure them on these issues.
But I cannot.
